Flock of ca. 50 large dark swifts circling on coast - initially identified as Common Swifts but the birds were very vocal (not usual in common swift on wintering grounds). Sound initially reminiscent of African Black Swift but more mellow and lower pitched. Birds seemed rather lazy in circling about. Appeared paler than typical common swift, but no other features noted at the time. 

The swifts circled above the lodge for about 20 minutes and then, as the light diminished appeared to move off in a north-easterly direction, out towards the ocean.  Helpful comments on recording received initially by Brian Finch and Guy Kirwan. Detailed sound analysis done with assistance of Gary Allport and Faansie Peacock on confusion possibilities concluded that this call is indeed that of Apus berliozi.   An account of sound analysis will be submitted to the BOC Bulletin    See also  recording set Identification of Large Dark Swifts in Southern Africa  -  https://www.xeno-canto.org/set/5842

This is partly a mystery call.  The opening call was delivered by a Lesser Moorhen which flew and landed giving the call on the recording as it landed and then a series of clucks afterwards.  It sounds very like a Little Grebe but it was definitely a Lesser Moorhen.  I then had two further phrases delivered from the same area of flooded vegetation but coudlnt see the bird - but there was however a Little Grebe in sight about 30yds away.  On the spectro the calls look identical to me so I think theyre all L Moorhens.  Listening to the opening call it does sound very like a Little Grebe but is discernibly different.  I would value comments.

The call (song) was a series of 8-10 repeated creaky notes in rapid succession, delivered as a phrase once every 5 seconds or so (11 repetitions in this 58s clip).  A second bird was either answering or maybe dueting as a more subtle quieter and lower toned response.    It's not clear if the cluck at 43s is a Moorhen (which were also present) or a Lesser Moorhen.  This call was delivered before dawn and continued until about 90 minues after sunrise.

This is the second recording of one of two Steppe Whimbrels N p alboaxillaris found in Maputo Bay, Mozambique in February 2016. There are many photos available of these birds. This bird is thought to be a male and this bubbling call was recorded as part of a dispute with an adjacent Whimbrel (N. p. phaeopus) over a low tide feeding territory. The call is atypical for this bird - it normally does a longer bubbling call which is as yet unrecorded.

The two birds start calling almost in synchrony but the alboaxillaris is the one calling for longer at the end of the recording with the slightly more exagerated note structure.  The N. p. phaeopus is calling similar to the 'whining' call described in BWP.

This is a recording of the call of an alboaxillaris 'Steppe' Whimbrel, with a nominate phaeopus calling further away, once.  The first phrase right at the beginning is clipped and the second complete call is of the alboaxillaris.  The third more distant call is of  anominate phaeopus, and the fourth and fitfth calls are of the alboaxillaris).  The calls are all of the 'tittering' call (cf Birds of the Western Palearctic species account).

This is the only recording so far of one of two Steppe Whimbrels N p alboaxillaris found in Maputo Bay, Mozambique in February 2016.  There are many photos available of these birds.  This bird is thought to be a male and this snatch of bubbling call was recorded immediately before a dispute with an adjacent Whimbrel over a low tide feeding territory.  The call is abbreviated and atypical for this bird - it normally does a longer bubbling call which is as yet unrecorded.

Unusual sub-song introduction to the trill call typical of S. w. whytii and S. w. minima.  This call is typical of birds in miombo woodland from Mulanje, Malawi and east through northern Mozambique and southern and eastern Tanzania north to coastal Kenya.  But birds west of the highlands in Malawi and the Eastern Arc Mountains (Tanzania) through Kenya to Ethiopia have a very different call and are much closer to Long-billed Crombec, S. rufescens.  I have no doubt that the whytii complex is polyphyletic as currently recognized but further studies are needed to tease out the relationships between the various forms of "whytii" and rufescens.  There are probably at least 3 species involved.

Two recordings both with terrible wind noise but two repititions of the slurring double note flight song are audible in the middle of this recording.   Note that it is unusual for these longclaws to be singing at this time of year.  The breeding season here is October-Feb but unusual weather due to El Nino meant no rains in the usual seasons and, unusual recent heavy rain.  The grassland is thus wet and verdant and presumably the birds are at least stimulated to sing and maybe are breeding.

loc: Marracuene District, Marracuene District, Maputo Province
rmk: This is in a grassy steppe with some tidal influx at Spring Tides so it was impossible to get closer. Howver, we suspect it is a female Black Coucal calling. Since a few months they are present in numbers along the dune edge rice fields (at least 6 territories) but this would be a new, quite distant location.
Suspected Scrub-Robin, bearded, brown or white-browed?

We played Samuel Jones' recording of Artisornis sousae XC345932 and had the impression that a bird was coming closer and closer in the undergrowth along the stream and responding, not with a typical call but just a few short notes "piew" "piew", not much to go on as we did not make visual contact. Could it be?
Close to camp, in the miombo at around 1400 m
In a valley bottom of high intact rainforest, a repetitive shattering call/song. We think possibly Evergreen Forest Warbler (we got "pics" of the tail.

loc: Lipilichi Wilderness, Main Camp, Pauila, Sanga, Niassa
rmk: Second recording of a rather varied, creative and melodious song. We have seen Basra Reed Warbler and Marsh Warbler not far upstream in the tangles along the dry river bed (riverine forest but where there are no big trees there are tangles).

rmk: This sounds like a francolin/spurfowl of sorts. We did see a pair of Crested Francolin much later and much further down the riverine forest winding through the miombo/bushed grassland

loc: Lipilichi Wilderness, Main Camp, Pauila, Sanga, Niassa
rmk: The recording starts with some insect noise, then after about 15 seconds there is a weak owl call, at 1 minute the owl call is very clear, we think a duet and we suspect Southern White-faced Owl Ptilopsis grant. We found pellets and from the description of the rangers that seems to most likely.

This song was recorded whilst searching for a Blackcap Sylvia atricapilla seen a few days earlier, including playing the song.  This bird apparently responded to the song but remained hidden whilst continuously singing for around 25 minutes (when we left).  The bird seemed to stay stationary ca 8m from the ground in the centre of a thick bushy area at the base of a large tree.  

The bird sounded similar to certain part so the song of African Yellow White-eye  Zosterops senegalensis but did not at time use the full characteristic flutey song  (which I hear every day in my garden).  It did do some White-eye-sounding phrases (not on the recording) but these actually sounded more like mimicry than a white-eye to my ear, not having the depth/ richness.

It sounds to me like a bird in subsong and it could just be a white-eye doing that but if so it delivered the song unbroken from the same spot for a long time - which does not sound like subsonging to me. 

Other options that came to mind were Yellow-fronted Canary  Serinus mozambicus which seems unlikely buried in the middle of a bush, and again doesn't have the fullness of song.  Garden Warbler S. borin or Blackcap, frankly neither of which sound right either. 

I would be grateful for comments.

loc: First Wetland Zone 4, Macaneta, Incomati Delta, Marracuene District, Maputo Province
rmk: A Baillon's Crake was flushed going into the wetland and showed a few times then disappeared before the recorded call started. The thrilling warbling sound therefore is possibly the Baillon's Crake but it is not its usual clockwork stuff, more like a Black Crake. That species is common in the area also but usually excludes Bailon's from its broad reedbeds while this is a narrow 2-3 m wide reedbed on a brackish tidal channel rather typical for Baillon's Crake in our experience of several years there. African Rail is also a regular caller in that corning.

Editing: High-pass filter, some amplification, noise reduction.

Recorder: Olympus WS-822

Microphone: None

loc: First Wetland Zone 4, Macaneta, Incomati Delta, Marracuene District, Maputo Province
rmk:
This is one of the few permanent wetlands in this part of the tidal delta. It is low-lying and accumulates rainwater from a large area and is also reached by the highest Spring tides around the Equinox, probably only over 3.75 m AMSL. During the dry season, the waters become highly saline. During the recording, agter some good rains, it was 6.25 ppt.
It has mainly sedges including Cyperus articulatus) and reeds (Phragmites). 
Many normally "rare" wetland species are currently present in the Incomati Delta, Lesser Moorhen, Allen's Gallinule, Dwarf Bittern, etc. The call is a faint repetitive clucking.
Two birds singing in the forest edge undergrowth. Recording edited. Only one heard on this recording. Found during trip with Grahame Snow.
